a. Download the file and merge into the single data using SEQN Variable.

  • save I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\VIX_D.dta, replace

  • file I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\VIX_D.dta saved

  • import sasxport5 I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\DEMO_D.XPT, clear

  • save I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\DEMO_D.dta, replace

  • file I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\DEMO_D.dta saved

  • use I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\VIX_D.dta

  • merge 1:1 seqn using I:\Fall 2023\STATS 506\PS3\DEMO_D.dta

  • . keep if _merge==3

(3,368 observations deleted)

b)

Proportion of respondents within each 10-year bracket who wear glasses/contact lenses for distance vision

  • gen age_bracket = floor(ridageyr / 10) * 10

  • collapse (mean) wear_glasses = viq220 (count) total = viq220, by(age_bracket)

  • list age_bracket wear_glasses

c) Logistic Regression

Model 1: age

  • logistic viq220 ridageyr

  • logit viq220 ridageyr

  • estat ic

  • estimates store Model1

Model 2: age, race, gender

  • logistic viq220 ridageyr ridreth1 riagendr

  • logit viq220 ridageyr ridreth1 riagendr

  • estat ic

  • estimates store Model2

Model 3 age, race, gender, Poverty Income ratio

  • logistic viq220 ridageyr ridreth1 riagendr indfmpir

  • logit viq220 ridageyr ridreth1 riagendr indfmpir

  • estat ic

  • estimates store Model3

  • esttab Model1 Model2 Model3, b aic pr2

    d) We can use chi-square test to measure the goodness of fit.

  • tabulate riagendr viq220, chi2

If we look at the chi-square test and p-value, it is almost equal to 0. We can conclude that there is a statistically significant difference between the glasses wear between men and women.

###Question (a)

# Define the SQL query to merge film and langauge by language_id
query <- "
SELECT f.*, l.name AS language_name
FROM film AS f
LEFT JOIN language AS l ON f.language_id = l.language_id
"

# Execute the query and retrieve the result
result <- dbGetQuery(sakila, query)

# Print the merged result
print(result)

#Find the most common language using dyplyr through grouping the tables by language name 
most_common_language <- result %>%
  group_by(language_name) %>%
  summarize(film_count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(film_count))

sum((result$language_name=="English"))

###Question (b)

gg("SELECT c.name AS genre_name, COUNT(*) AS movie_count
FROM film_category AS fc
INNER JOIN category AS c ON fc.category_id = c.category_id
GROUP BY c.name
ORDER BY movie_count DESC
LIMIT 1;")
##   genre_name movie_count
## 1     Sports          74
# Find the most common genre and its count using R
#library(tidyverse)

movie = gg("SELECT *
   FROM film_category")
category = gg("SELECT *
              FROM category")

genre = merge(x=movie, y=category, by="category_id", all.x=TRUE)

most_common_genre = aggregate(genre$film_id, by=list(genre$name), FUN=length)
most_common_genre[order(most_common_genre$x, decreasing=TRUE),]
##        Group.1  x
## 15      Sports 74
## 9      Foreign 73
## 8       Family 69
## 6  Documentary 68
## 2    Animation 66
## 1       Action 64
## 13         New 63
## 7        Drama 62
## 10       Games 61
## 14      Sci-Fi 61
## 3     Children 60
## 5       Comedy 58
## 4     Classics 57
## 16      Travel 57
## 11      Horror 56
## 12       Music 51

We can see that sports is the most common genre.

gg("SELECT country, COUNT(*) AS customer_count
FROM (
    SELECT c.country, COUNT(*) AS customer_count
    FROM customer AS cu
    INNER JOIN address AS a ON cu.address_id = a.address_id
    INNER JOIN city AS ci ON a.city_id = ci.city_id
    INNER JOIN country AS c ON ci.country_id = c.country_id
    GROUP BY c.country_id, c.country
) AS merged
GROUP BY country
HAVING customer_count = 9;")
##          country customer_count
## 1 United Kingdom              1
# Combine data from customer, address, city, and country tables into a single DataFrame
query <- "
SELECT c.*, a.*, ci.*, co.*
FROM customer AS c
JOIN address AS a ON c.address_id = a.address_id
JOIN city AS ci ON a.city_id = ci.city_id
JOIN country AS co ON ci.country_id = co.country_id
"
combined_data <- dbGetQuery(sakila, query)

# Find which country has exactly 9 customers
country_counts <- table(combined_data$country)
countries_with_9_customers <- names(country_counts[country_counts == 9])

print(countries_with_9_customers)
## [1] "United Kingdom"

UK is the country that has 9 customers.

###Question (a)

# Count the number of email addresses with ".net" TLD
num_net_emails <- sum(grepl("@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\\.net", us500$email))

# Calculate the proportion
proportion_net <- num_net_emails / nrow(us500)

# Print the result

## Proportion of email addresses with '.net' TLD: 0.14

###Question (b)

# Function to check if an email address has at least one non-alphanumeric character
has_non_alphanumeric <- function(email) {
  # Use regular expression to match non-alphanumeric characters (excluding "@" and ".")
  non_alphanumeric <- grep("[^A-Za-z0-9@.]", email)
  # If any non-alphanumeric character is found, return TRUE, otherwise, return FALSE
  return(length(non_alphanumeric) > 0)
}

# Apply the function to each email address in the dataset and count the number of emails with non-alphanumeric characters
num_emails_with_non_alphanumeric <- sum(sapply(us500$email, has_non_alphanumeric))

# Calculate the proportion
proportion_non_alphanumeric <- num_emails_with_non_alphanumeric / nrow(us500)

# Print the result
cat("Proportion of email addresses with non-alphanumeric characters (excluding '@' and '.'):",
    proportion_non_alphanumeric, "\n")
## Proportion of email addresses with non-alphanumeric characters (excluding '@' and '.'): 0.248

###Question (c)

# Combine phone1 and phone2 columns into a single vector
phone_numbers <- c(us500$phone1, us500$phone2)

# Extract the area code (first 3 digits) from each phone number using regular expressions
area_codes <- gsub("^(\\d{3}).*$", "\\1", phone_numbers)

# Calculate the frequency of each area code
area_code_counts <- table(area_codes)

# Find the most common area code
most_common_area_code <- names(area_code_counts[which.max(area_code_counts)])

cat("The most common area code among all phone numbers is:", most_common_area_code, "\n")
## The most common area code among all phone numbers is: 973

###Question (D)

library (dplyr)
library(stringr)

# Extract apartment numbers using regular expressions and take the logarithm
apartment_numbers <- us500$address %>%
  # Extract apartment numbers using regular expression
  str_extract("\\b\\d+\\b") %>%
  # Remove NAs (addresses with no apartment numbers)
  na.omit() %>%
  # Convert to numeric and take the logarithm (base 10)
  as.numeric() %>%
  log10()

# Create a histogram of the logarithm of apartment numbers
hist(apartment_numbers, main = "Histogram of Logarithm of Apartment Numbers",
     xlab = "Logarithm (Base 10) of Apartment Numbers")

###Question (e)

# Extract the apartment numbers (last couple of numbers before # sign)
apartment_numbers <- gsub(".*#(\\d+)$", "\\1", us500$address)

# Remove NAs (addresses with no apartment numbers)
apartment_numbers <- apartment_numbers[!is.na(apartment_numbers)]

# Extract the first digit from the apartment numbers
first_digits <- as.numeric(substr(apartment_numbers, 1, 1))

# Create a histogram of the first digits
hist(first_digits, main = "Histogram of First Digits in Apartment Numbers",
     xlab = "First Digit", ylim = c(0, max(table(first_digits))))

We can see that it does not follow the Benfords law as the distribution is spread out evenly among each digit.

###Question (f)

# Extract apartment numbers (numbers after # sign)
apartment_numbers <- gsub(".*#(\\d+).*", "\\1", us500$address)

# Remove NAs (addresses with no apartment numbers)
apartment_numbers <- apartment_numbers[!is.na(apartment_numbers)]

# Extract the last digit from apartment numbers
last_digits <- as.numeric(substring(apartment_numbers, nchar(apartment_numbers), nchar(apartment_numbers)))
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
# Create a histogram of the last digits
hist(last_digits, main = "Histogram of Last Digits in Apartment Numbers",
     xlab = "Last Digit", ylim = c(0, max(table(last_digits))))

The last digits of apartment numbers somewhat follows the Benfords Law in a way that the distribution is bimodal and the data points are more focused on the first couple digits.
